      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'An open concept kitchen remodel in Seattle typically costs $35,000 to $100,000 or more depending on scope. Removing a non-load-bearing wall costs $1,500 to $5,000. Removing a load-bearing wall with a structural beam runs $5,000 to $15,000. A full open concept remodel including new kitchen finishes, island, lighting, and flooring averages $50,000 to $85,000 in the Seattle market.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How do I know if a wall is load-bearing?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Load-bearing walls typically run perpendicular to floor joists, are located near the center of the house, and support walls or roof structure above. However, you should never guess — always hire a licensed structural engineer to evaluate. In Seattle, a structural assessment costs $500 to $1,500 and is required before obtaining a permit for wall removal. Many Seattle Craftsman and mid-century homes have load-bearing walls where homeowners do not expect them.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do I need a permit to remove a wall in Seattle?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes, in most cases. The Seattle Department of Construction and Inspections (SDCI) requires a building permit for removing load-bearing walls, and often for non-load-bearing walls if electrical, plumbing, or HVAC modifications are involved. Permit costs range from $300 to $2,000. Working without a permit can result in fines, difficulty selling your home, and insurance complications.' },
